  "prompt": "What are some of the best stories about Virender Sehwag?",
  "response": "Virender Sehwag is a walking legend, and his career is overflowing with hilarious anecdotes and inspiring stories. Here are a few of the best, categorized for easier browsing:\n\n**On-Field Brilliance and Audacity:**\n\n*   **The Multan Ka Sultan (Multan's Sultan):**  Arguably his most famous story.  While batting in the 2004 Test match against Pakistan in Multan, Sachin Tendulkar, at the non-striker's end, tried to give Sehwag advice to slow down as he approached 300.  Sehwag famously asked Sachin what was the instruction coming from the captain (Rahul Dravid). Sachin said, \"He said play your natural game.\" Sehwag then casually responded, \"Rahul bhai ko bolo viru is already playing his natural game, he is trying to hit a six.\" He went on to hit a six off Saqlain Mushtaq to become the first Indian to score a triple century in Test cricket.  The sheer audacity of attempting a six to reach a triple century, and then actually pulling it off, is legendary.\n\n*   **Humayun\u2019s Tomb Diversion:** During a Test match in Sri Lanka, Sehwag was nearing a century.  When asked what he wanted as a gift, he nonchalantly said, \"Humayun\u2019s tomb.\" The commentators were baffled, until he clarified he was referring to Muttiah Muralitharan, a Sri Lankan bowler, and meant he wanted to hit him all over the park.\n\n*   **Singing While Batting:** Many stories circulate about Sehwag singing while batting, often classic Bollywood tunes.  He reportedly used it to stay relaxed and block out pressure. Some claim he even started a conversation with Shoaib Akhtar while singing!  The story perfectly encapsulates his carefree attitude.\n\n*   **Hitting the Fastest Triple Century:** In the 2008 Test against South Africa, Sehwag smashed the fastest triple century in Test history, reaching the milestone in just 278 balls. This showcased his incredible hand-eye coordination and fearless approach to batting. He simply kept attacking, regardless of the situation.\n\n*   **The Near Miss at 400:**  In the same innings against South Africa where he scored 319, he was dismissed agonizingly close to becoming only the third batsman to reach 400 in a Test innings.  While disappointing, it underscored his ability to dominate bowling attacks like few others could.\n\n**Off-Field Quips and Personality:**\n\n*   **'Beta Beta Hota Hai':**  During a Test match against Australia, Ricky Ponting tried to sledge Sehwag.  Sehwag, instead of getting into a verbal duel, simply told Ponting to ask Sachin Tendulkar about this. Apparently in a previous match, Sehwag had told Ponting that \"son is son and father is father\" when Ponting tried to sledge Sachin. The reference to Sachin's dominance over Ponting was enough to silence the Aussie captain.\n\n*   **\"Dekh ke Ball daal\" (Bowl Looking at the Ball):**  Another famous story involves Shoaib Akhtar, who often bowled bouncers at Sehwag.  Sehwag reportedly told Akhtar to \"bowl looking at the ball\" because he claimed Akhtar couldn't see the ball due to his own long hair.  The cheeky remark highlighted Sehwag's wit and confidence.\n\n*   **Practical Jokes on Teammates:** Sehwag was known to be a prankster in the dressing room.  Stories abound of him hiding teammates' belongings, changing their phone languages, and generally creating a light-hearted atmosphere.\n\n*   **Directness and Honesty:** Sehwag is known for his refreshingly honest and straightforward opinions.  He doesn't mince words and speaks his mind, even if it's controversial.  This quality has made him a popular commentator and pundit.\n\n*   **The Dairy Farm:**  After retirement, Sehwag started a dairy farm.  He has often spoken about his love for farming and his desire to reconnect with his roots.  This shows a different side of him, away from the glitz and glamour of cricket.\n\n**Leadership and Influence:**\n\n*   **Leading From the Front:**  When he was captain (for a brief period), Sehwag always encouraged aggressive cricket. He pushed his teammates to play with freedom and expressed that there's no use getting afraid of getting out.\n\n*   **Inspiring a Generation:**  Sehwag's fearless batting style inspired a generation of Indian batsmen to play with more freedom and aggression.  He showed that it was possible to dominate even the best bowlers in the world.\n\nThese are just a few of the many incredible stories about Virender Sehwag. His unique combination of audacious talent, a relaxed attitude, and a sharp wit made him one of the most entertaining and beloved cricketers of all time.  Search online for \"Virender Sehwag anecdotes\" or \"Virender Sehwag stories\" to find even more gems. His autobiography, \"View from the Dressing Room,\" is also a fantastic source of insights and stories.\n",
